# JOIN - Quick Notes (Data Engineer 5yr+)

## Core Concept
- JOIN = दोन tables common column वर merge करतो
- **Expensive operation** → nodes दरम्यान **data shuffle** होतो
- Rule: **Filter BEFORE JOIN** → shuffle कमी = fast query

---

## JOIN Types (Cheat Sheet)

| Type        | Output                              | Use Case                        |
|-------------|-------------------------------------|---------------------------------|
| INNER       | फक्त matching rows (दोन्हीकडे)     | Exact match हवे                 |
| LEFT        | सर्व left + matching right          | Master table सर्व rows हवे     |
| RIGHT       | सर्व right + matching left          | (क्वचित वापरतात, LEFT prefer)  |
| FULL OUTER  | दोन्हींचे सर्व rows                 | Data reconciliation             |
| LEFT SEMI   | Left rows जे match करतात (right columns नाही) | EXISTS check       |
| LEFT ANTI   | Left rows जे match करत **नाहीत**   | Missing/Unmatched records       |
| CROSS       | Cartesian product (n×m rows)        | ⚠️ टाळा - खूप महाग             |

---

## Data Explosion (Critical!)
- Non-unique keys → duplicate rows explode
- Left: 3 rows (id=1) × Right: 3 rows (id=1) = **9 rows output**
- **Fix:** JOIN नंतर `distinct()` किंवा आधीच deduplicate करा
- **Always verify:** दोन्ही sides च्या join keys unique आहेत का?

---

## PySpark Code Patterns

```python
# Basic
df1.join(df2, "common_col", "inner")

# Multi-column
df1.join(df2, (df1.col1 == df2.col1) & (df1.col2 == df2.col2), "left")

# Alias (ambiguous column fix)
df1.alias("a").join(df2.alias("b"), col("a.id") == col("b.id")) \
   .select("a.id", "b.name")

# OPTIMIZED - Filter BEFORE join
df1.filter("status = 'active'").join(df2, "id", "inner")

# Left Anti (missing records)
customers.join(orders, "customer_id", "leftanti").show()
```

